<doc id="438093" wikidata="Q1286721" url="?curid=438093" title="Lookback option">
<text>Lookback options, in the terminology of finance, are a type of exotic option with path dependency, among many other kind of options. The payoff depends on the optimal (maximum or minimum) underlying asset&#x27;s price occurring over the life of the option. The option allows the holder to &quot;look back&quot; over time to determine the payoff. There exist two kinds of lookback options: with floating strike and with fixed strike. 

==Lookback option with floating strike==
As the name introduces it, the option&#x27;s strike price is floating and determined at maturity. The floating strike is the optimal value of the underlying asset&#x27;s price during the option life. The payoff is the maximum difference between the market asset&#x27;s price at maturity and the floating strike. For the call, the strike price is fixed at the asset&#x27;s lowest price during the option&#x27;s life, and, for the put, it is fixed at the asset&#x27;s highest price. Note that these options are not really options, as they will be always exercised by their holder. In fact, the option is never out-of-the-money, which makes it more expensive than a standard option. The payoff functions for the lookback call and the lookback put, respectively, are given by:
:formula_1
where formula_2 is the asset&#x27;s maximum price during the life of the option, formula_3 is the asset&#x27;s minimum price during the life of the option, and formula_4 is the underlying asset&#x27;s price at maturity formula_5.

==Lookback option with fixed strike==
As for the standard European options, the option&#x27;s strike price is fixed. The difference is that the option is not exercised at the price at maturity: the payoff is the maximum difference between the optimal underlying asset price and the strike. For the call option, the holder chooses to exercise at the point when the underlying asset price is at its highest level. For the put option, the holder chooses to exercise at the underlying asset&#x27;s lowest price. The payoff functions for the lookback call and the lookback put, respectively, are given by:
:formula_6
where formula_2 is the asset&#x27;s maximum price during the life of the option, formula_3 is the asset&#x27;s minimum price during the life of the option, and formula_9 is the strike price.

==Arbitrage-free price of lookback options with floating strike==
Using the Black–Scholes model, and its notations, we can price the European lookback options with floating strike. The pricing method is much more complicated than for the standard European options and can be found in &quot;Musiela&quot;. Assume that there exists a continuously-compounded risk-free interest rate formula_10 and a constant stock&#x27;s volatility formula_11. Assume that the time to maturity is formula_12, and that we will price the option at time formula_13, although the life of the option started at time zero. Define formula_14. Finally, set that 
